    <div class="isyf-article-hero-content">
      <span class="isyf-article-hero-label">STYLE</span>
      <h1 class="isyf-article-hero-title">Building a Conscious Wardrobe</h1>
      <span class="isyf-article-hero-date">March 2026</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="isyf-article-body">
    <p class="isyf-article-intro">
      The most stylish people you know probably own fewer clothes than you think. A conscious wardrobe isn't about deprivation — it's about intention. It's choosing pieces that work harder, last longer, and make you feel something every time you wear them.
    </p>

    <h2>The myth of more</h2>

    <p>
      Somewhere along the way, we were sold the idea that style requires volume. New arrivals every week. A different outfit for every occasion. An overflowing wardrobe that still somehow leaves you with "nothing to wear." The fast fashion model thrives on this anxiety — the feeling that what you already own is never quite enough.
    </p>
    <p>
      But look at the people whose style you genuinely admire. Chances are, they've found their uniform — a set of silhouettes, colours, and textures that they return to again and again, in different combinations, for different moods. Their wardrobe isn't a collection of impulse purchases. It's a curated system.
    </p>

    <h2>Start with the foundation</h2>

    <p>
      A conscious wardrobe begins with foundation pieces — the garments you'll reach for three or four times a week without thinking. These should be the highest quality items you own, because they'll see the most wear. A well-cut crew-neck tee in white and black. A knit sweater in a neutral tone that works with everything. Trousers that fit properly and move with your body.
    </p>
    <p>
      At ISYF, our Premium line was built around this principle. Every piece in the collection was designed to be a foundation — not a statement. The Oversized Knit in cream. The Structured Blazer in sand. The Tailored Trouser in charcoal. These aren't exciting in isolation, but together they create a wardrobe that makes getting dressed feel effortless.
    </p>

    <h2>Add personality, not noise</h2>

    <p>
      Once your foundation is solid, personality comes through in the details. A graphic hoodie that says something you believe in. A cap that finishes the silhouette. A tote bag that carries your essentials and a message at the same time.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is where ISYF FEELS comes in. The streetwear line isn't about logos for the sake of logos — every print, every embroidery, every message is chosen because it means something. When you wear a FEELS piece, you're adding a layer of expression to a foundation that already works.
    </p>

    <h2>The colour palette that works</h2>

    <p>
      The simplest rule for building a wardrobe that works: stick to a palette. Ours is built on five tones:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Black</strong> — the anchor. Works alone, works with everything.</li>
      <li><strong>White</strong> — the counterpoint. Keeps things fresh and clean.</li>
      <li><strong>Cream / Beige</strong> — the warmth. Softens everything it touches.</li>
      <li><strong>Charcoal</strong> — the alternative to black. More subtle, equally versatile.</li>
      <li><strong>Navy</strong> — the quiet option. Refined without being obvious.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      With these five colours, every piece in your wardrobe can pair with every other piece. No more standing in front of the mirror wondering if things "go together." They always do.
    </p>

    <h2>Quality over quantity — what to look for</h2>

    <p>
      When you buy fewer pieces, each purchase matters more. Here's what to look for:
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Fabric weight.</strong> Hold the garment in your hand. Does it feel substantial? A good t-shirt should weigh 180-220 grams per square metre. A quality hoodie should be at least 350gsm. Lightweight doesn't mean premium — it usually means it won't last.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Construction.</strong> Turn the garment inside out. Are the seams clean and even? Are they reinforced at stress points (shoulders, underarms, hems)? Flat-felled seams on t-shirts are a sign of quality. Double-stitched hems mean the brand cares about longevity.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Fit.</strong> The garment should follow your body's proportions without pulling or bunching. Pay attention to shoulder seams (they should sit at the edge of your shoulder for a fitted piece, or slightly past for an oversized silhouette). The hem should fall at a consistent length all around.
    </p>

    <h2>Care is part of the equation</h2>

    <p>
      A conscious wardrobe isn't just about buying better — it's about maintaining what you have. Wash less frequently (most garments only need washing every 3-4 wears unless visibly dirty). Wash cold. Air dry when possible. Store knitwear folded, not hung. These small habits extend the life of your clothes by years.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      "Buy less, choose well, make it last."
      <cite>— Vivienne Westwood</cite>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>The 30-wear test</h2>

    <p>
      Before buying anything, ask yourself: will I wear this at least 30 times? If the answer isn't an immediate yes, walk away. This simple test eliminates impulse purchases, trend-driven buys, and the kind of "it was on sale" decisions that fill wardrobes with things we never actually wear.
    </p>
    <p>
      A conscious wardrobe takes time to build. It's not something you achieve in a single shopping trip. It's an ongoing process of refining, replacing, and recommitting to the idea that less — when it's the right less — is genuinely more.
    </p>
  </div>

